The '''Pemba sunbird''' ('''''Cinnyris pembae''''') is a species of bird in the [[sunbird]] family. It is [[endemism|endemic]] to [[Pemba Island]], [[Tanzania]].

==Taxonomy==
[[Anton Reichenow]] first described the Pemba sunbird in 1905.{{sfn|Reichenow|1918|p=98}}

The taxonomy of the Pemba sunbird has been the subject of debate. Pakenham regarded it as a subspecies of the [[purple-banded sunbird]] under the name ''Cinnyris bifasciatus pembae''.{{sfn|Pakenham|1936|p=268}} It is also sometimes regarded as conspecific with the [[violet-breasted sunbird]], ''Cinnyris chalcomelas'', which lives on the mainland in Kenya.{{sfn|Stevenson|Fanshawe|2002|p=454}} ''Cinnyris pembae'' is distinguished from these closely related species by being the only purple-banded sunbird on Pemba Island.{{sfn|Cheke|Mann|Allen|2001|p=124}} It is also [[insular dwarfism|significantly smaller]] than its fellow sunbirds.{{sfn|Cheke|Mann|Allen|2001|p=124}} [[Hermann Grote]] regarded the Pemba sunbird to be identical in coloration, but about half the size, of ''Cinnyris voeltzkowi'' (today recognized as a subspecies of the [[Malagasy green sunbird]], ''Cinnyris notatus'').{{sfn|Grote|1930|p=12}}

==Description==
Males have a wingspan of 51.5-53 mm, while females have a wingspan of 47.5-50 mm.{{sfn|Clancey|Williams|1967|p=29}} Adult males display iridescent blue-green coloration on their head and throat with bluish violet coloration on their wings and across their breast.{{sfn|Clancey|Williams|1967|p=29}}{{sfn|eBird}} Females have a gray-brown coloration on their head and wings, a pale yellow underside with blurry streaking and a small pale yellow lateral streak posterior to the eye.{{sfn|Clancey|Williams|1967|p=29}}{{sfn|eBird}}  Juveniles resemble adult females with darker chin and throat, broad whitish malar stripe, and mottled grey underparts.{{sfn|Cheke|Mann|Allen|2001|p=124}}

==Behavior==
Pemba sunbirds consume nectar and fruits. They have been observed nesting in ''[[Meliosma|Wellingtonia]]'' trees and consuming the trees' nectar.{{sfn|Pakenham|1936|p=268}} Other favored foods include the white berries of ''[[Flueggea virosa]]'', into which the Pemba sunbird jabs its beak, while smaller berries are eaten whole.{{sfn|Cheke|Mann|Allen|2001|p=124}}

Breeding takes place throughout the year with a noted lull between the months of January and April, inclusive.{{sfn|Pakenham|1943|p=187}} Males exhibit aggression to each other during breeding season.{{sfn|Cheke|Mann|Allen|2001|p=124}} Nesting takes place approximately from July through December.{{sfn|Pakenham|1936|p=268}} Greenish-white eggs with brown streaks are laid in a "bag or purse-shaped nest suspended 1-2 m up from shrub or amongst foliage."{{sfn|Cheke|Mann|Allen|2001|p=124}}

The Pemba sunbird is known for a repetitive ''tslink-tslink-tslink'' call which is unlike that of its relatives on the mainland.{{sfn|Archer|Turner|1993|p=96}} It can be found in a wide variety of habitats on Pemba Island.{{sfn|Cheke|Mann|Allen|2001|p=124}}

